      "id": 146873910,
      "body": "Don't be discouraged.  The word \u201cobvious\u201d has a special secret meaning in mathematics. It definitely doesn't mean \u201cself-evident.\u201d An obvious proposition in math is often like a Zen koan. You can break your head over it for weeks or years, and then (maybe) lightning strikes and you understand why it is called obvious.\n\nAnother fun mathematical term is \u201csimple.\u201d  In about the seventh hour of (I kid you not) a seminar on complexity theory, my advisor was going on about \"simple sets,\" and then he started talking about \"hypersimple sets.\" I made the mistake of asking whether a hypersimple set is one that is way simpler than a simple set.  Quick as a rattlesnake, he stood me up and demanded the (not simple) definition of a simple set, which fortunately I was able to produce. But I was in the doghouse for a while after that.  By the way, there are also hyperhypersimple sets, which you might think must be really bloody obvious sets.",
      "body_json": {
        "type": "doc",
        "attrs": {
          "schemaVersion": "v1"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Don't be discouraged. The word \u201cobvious\u201d has a special secret meaning in mathematics. It definitely doesn't mean \u201cself-evident.\u201d An obvious proposition in math is often like a Zen koan. You can break your head over it for weeks or years, and then (maybe) lightning strikes and you understand why it is called obvious."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Another fun mathematical term is \u201csimple.\u201d In about the seventh hour of (I kid you not) a seminar on complexity theory, my advisor was going on about \"simple sets,\" and then he started talking about \"hypersimple sets.\" I made the mistake of asking whether a hypersimple set is one that is way simpler than a simple set. Quick as a rattlesnake, he stood me up and demanded the (not simple) definition of a simple set, which fortunately I was able to produce. But I was in the doghouse for a while after that. By the way, there are also hyperhypersimple sets, which you might think must be really bloody obvious sets."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
